{# ===== faq ===== #}
<section class="blk" id="faq">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="shead reveal">
      <div class="lab">Straight answers</div>
      <h2>The questions every first call starts with</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="faqwrap stagger" style="max-width:820px">
      <div class="faq"><div class="faq-q">How much does a pole barn cost in Michigan?</div>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>It depends on size, concrete, doors, insulation, and site work, which is why we quote every building to order instead of posting a price list. The estimate is free: Zosim walks your site, talks through what you need, and gives you a written number. That number is the one we build to.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq"><div class="faq-q">How long does a build take?</div>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Once concrete is in, the structure on a typical garage goes up in a day or two. The honest answer for the whole project is that permits and Michigan weather set the pace, so we give you a realistic window up front and tell you right away if it moves.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq"><div class="faq-q">Do you handle permits?</div>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Yes. We put together the permit package, drawings, and truss details and work with your township or city building department. Which office that is depends on your address, and we deal with these offices across Oakland, Genesee, Lapeer, and Macomb counties all the time.</p></div></div>
      <div class="faq"><div class="faq-q">Should I build post-frame or steel?</div>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Post-frame wins on cost for most garages, barns, and homes. Pre-engineered steel wins when you need big clear spans or a fire-resistant shell, like arenas, hangars, and industrial space. We build both, so you get a straight comparison instead of a pitch for the only system we sell.</p></div></div>
    </div>
    <p class="reveal" style="margin-top:16px"><a href="/blog/steel-building-vs-pole-barn/">Read the full steel vs. pole barn comparison &rarr;</a></p>
  </div>
</section>

